            "params": [],
            "text": "{\"messages\":[{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"i need to deploy a multi site evpn vxlan design, (6 nexus, 3 VPC pairs site) i'll need help to figure out the physical connectivity and best practices for deployment\"},{\"role\":\"assistant\",\"content\":\"# VXLAN EVPN Multi-Site Design: 3-Site Deployment (6 Nexus, 3 VPC Pairs)\\n\\n## Architecture Overview\\n\\nBased on the Cisco VXLAN EVPN Multi-Site Design and Deployment white paper, your deployment maps to the **Border Gateway (BGW) VPC pair per site** model — the recommended pattern for production DCI scenarios providing both redundancy and scale containment.\\n\\n```\\nSite A                    Site B                    Site C\\n┌─────────────┐           ┌─────────────┐           ┌─────────────┐\\n│  BGW-A1     │           │  BGW-B1     │           │  BGW-C1     │\\n│  BGW-A2     │◄─────────►│  BGW-B2     │◄─────────►│  BGW-C2     │\\n│  (vPC pair) │           │  (vPC pair) │           │  (vPC pair) │\\n└──────┬──────┘           └──────┬──────┘           └──────┬──────┘\\n       │                         │                         │\\n  Site-Internal             Site-Internal             Site-Internal\\n  VXLAN Fabric              VXLAN Fabric              VXLAN Fabric\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Physical Connectivity\\n\\n### Inter-Site (DCI) Links\\n\\nEach BGW pair connects to every other site's BGW pair. With 3 sites, this forms a **full mesh of DCI links**:\\n\\n```\\nBGW-A1 ──── BGW-B1\\nBGW-A1 ──── BGW-B2\\nBGW-A2 ──── BGW-B1\\nBGW-A2 ──── BGW-B2\\n\\nBGW-A1 ──── BGW-C1\\nBGW-A1 ──── BGW-C2\\nBGW-A2 ──── BGW-C1\\nBGW-A2 ──── BGW-C2\\n\\nBGW-B1 ──── BGW-C1\\nBGW-B1 ──── BGW-C2\\nBGW-B2 ──── BGW-C1\\nBGW-B2 ──── BGW-C2\\n```\\n\\n> **Key design rule:** Each BGW must have a direct physical link to each remote BGW. Do **not** rely solely on vPC peer links for DCI reachability — each node must independently form EVPN BGP sessions to remote BGWs.\\n\\n### Intra-Site (BGW to Fabric) Links\\n\\nEach BGW pair connects into the site fabric as **spine-layer or dedicated border devices**:\\n\\n```\\n         Spine-1    Spine-2\\n           │  │      │  │\\n           │  └──────┘  │\\n         BGW-1        BGW-2\\n           └────vPC─────┘\\n```\\n\\n- BGWs connect to spines via **routed point-to-point links** (not vPC to spines)\\n- The vPC peer-link between the two BGWs carries only BUM/control-plane traffic — **not** DCI transit traffic\\n\\n---\\n\\n## vPC Pair Design for BGWs\\n\\n### vPC Peer Link & Keepalive\\n\\n| Link | Recommendation |\\n|------|---------------|\\n| vPC Peer-Link | Dedicated 10/40/100G trunk — minimum 2x links in port-channel |\\n| vPC Keepalive | Out-of-band management network (separate VRF) |\\n| Peer-Gateway | **Enable** — required for EVPN Multi-Site ARP/MAC handling |\\n| Delay Restore | 180s minimum — allows BGP to converge before forwarding |\\n\\n### Critical vPC + EVPN Multi-Site Config Considerations\\n\\n```\\n# Both BGWs must have the same:\\n- VTEP NVE loopback (anycast IP — shared between vPC peers)\\n- BGP AS number (same ASN within a site)\\n- evpn multisite border-gateway <site-id>  ← unique per SITE, same on both BGWs in pair\\n```\\n\\nThe **anycast VTEP IP** (shared loopback) is what the vPC pair advertises as a single logical VTEP to both the local fabric and remote sites.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Control Plane: BGP Design\\n\\n### eBGP Between Sites (Recommended)\\n\\n```\\nSite A ASN: 65001\\nSite B ASN: 65002\\nSite C ASN: 65003\\n```\\n\\n- Use **eBGP between BGWs across DCI** — provides natural policy boundaries and AS-path loop prevention\\n- Use **iBGP within each site** between BGWs and spines (route reflector on spines)\\n- EVPN address family enabled on all BGP sessions\\n\\n### BGP Session Matrix per BGW\\n\\nEach BGW-A1 peers with:\\n- BGW-A2 (iBGP, same site)\\n- BGW-B1, BGW-B2 (eBGP, Site B)\\n- BGW-C1, BGW-C2 (eBGP, Site C)\\n\\n> The CVD recommends **direct BGP sessions** between every BGW pair rather than route reflection across sites — keeps failure domains clean and avoids tromboning.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Data Plane: VXLAN Encapsulation\\n\\n### Multi-Site Re-encapsulation\\n\\nThis is the **critical architectural differentiator** of EVPN Multi-Site:\\n\\n```\\nSite A Fabric VTEP → [VXLAN] → BGW-A → [Re-encapsulate with site VTEP] → DCI → BGW-B → [Re-encapsulate with site VTEP] → Site B Fabric\\n```\\n\\n- BGWs **strip and re-encapsulate** VXLAN headers at site boundaries\\n- This **contains BUM flooding** within each site — remote sites only see BGW as the VTEP, not every leaf\\n- VNIs must be **consistent across sites** for L2 extension (same L2VNI mapped to same VLAN)\\n\\n### Underlay for DCI\\n\\n- Dedicated **routed L3 underlay** between BGW pairs (OSPF or static, keep it simple)\\n- BGW loopbacks must be reachable across DCI for VTEP-to-VTEP VXLAN tunnels\\n- **Do not stretch the intra-site underlay** across DCI — maintain separate underlay routing domains per site\\n\\n---\\n\\n## IP Addressing Scheme (Recommended)\\n\\n```\\n# Per Site — Loopbacks\\nSite A:\\n  BGW-A1 Router Loopback:    10.A.0.1/32\\n  BGW-A2 Router Loopback:    10.A.0.2/32\\n  Anycast VTEP Loopback:     10.A.0.100/32  ← advertised to both fabric and DCI\\n  BGW-A1 vPC Secondary:      10.A.0.101/32  ← physical VTEP for BGW-A1\\n\\n# DCI P2P Links (per pair of BGWs)\\nBGW-A1 ↔ BGW-B1:  10.255.0.0/31\\nBGW-A1 ↔ BGW-B2:  10.255.0.2/31\\nBGW-A2 ↔ BGW-B1:  10.255.0.4/31\\nBGW-A2 ↔ BGW-B2:  10.255.0.6/31\\n... (continue pattern for A↔C, B↔C)\\n```\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Key Design Best Practices (CVD-Aligned)\\n\\n| Consideration | Recommendation |\\n|---------------|----------------|\\n| BGW role | Dedicated — do not combine BGW and spine roles in small fabrics |\\n| Site ID | Unique integer per site, consistent on both BGWs in a pair |\\n| L2VNI consistency | Same VNI-to-VLAN mapping across all sites for extended segments |\\n| Route leaking | Use L3VNI / VRF at BGW for inter-VRF routing — avoid hairpinning through fabric |\\n| BUM handling | Ingress replication (IR) preferred for DCI — no multicast dependency across WAN |\\n| NX-OS version | Validate Multi-Site feature support — NX-OS 9.2(1)+ recommended minimum |\\n| MTU | **1600 bytes minimum** on DCI links to accommodate double VXLAN encapsulation overhead |\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Deployment Sequence\\n\\n1. **Build and validate each site fabric independently** (spines, leaves, VTEP configs)\\n2. **Configure BGW vPC pairs** within each site — verify intra-site EVPN before touching DCI\\n3. **Bring up DCI underlay** (P2P links, loopback reachability)\\n4. **Enable `evpn multisite border-gateway`** on BGWs with consistent site-IDs\\n5. **Establish eBGP EVPN sessions** between BGWs across sites\\n6. **Extend VNIs selectively** — don't stretch everything by default, only what's needed\\n7. **Verify with NGOAM** end-to-end path tracing (supported NX-OS 7.0(3)I7(1)+)\\n\\n---\\n\\n## What to Tackle Next\\n\\nGiven the scope, I'd recommend we work through these in sequence:\\n\\n- **BGP policy design** — route-maps, communities, AS-path filtering between sites\\n- **VRF and L3VNI design** — tenant segmentation across sites\\n- **BUM/multicast vs. ingress replication decision** for your DCI transport\\n- **QoS on DCI links** — DSCP marking preservation across re-encapsulation\\n\\nWhich area do you want to drill into first?\"},{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":\"i need to deploy a multi site evpn vxlan design, (6 nexus, 3 VPC pairs site) i'll need help to figure out the physical connectivity and best practices for deployment\"}]}"
          }
        },
